The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Police have recovered diamond jewellery and other ornaments (worth Rs 15 lakh) stolen from the Baguiati house of a promoter. Atul Das, 35, and wife Rita, 30, have been arrested in connection with the theft. North 24-Parganas police superintendent Praveen Kumar said Rita worked as a domestic help at the promoter?s house. Early last month, Rita and her husband made a duplicate key to the safe and stole the jewellery. Officers from Baguiati police station raided the Das?s house in Gouranga Nagar on Sunday night and recovered the jewellery. 

 Five persons arrested in connection with the murder of housewife Sagarika Das in Behala were produced in sub-judicial magistrate?s court in Alipore on Monday. They have been remanded in jail custody till July 25. Sagarika, wife of Subir Das, sustained serious burns on June 5 and died at SSKM Hospital on July 7. Her father, Sujit Karmakar, lodged an FIR with Behala police station on Sunday, alleging that his daughter had been killed by her husband and in-laws. Subir, his mother, sister, elder brother and his wife were arrested. 

 A 10-year-old schoolgirl was run over by a truck in Bishnupur, on the southern fringes of the city, on Monday. Police said the victim was going to school. She was rushed to a local hospital, where doctors pronounced her dead. The truck driver fled, leaving behind his vehicle.

 Police recovered the mutilated bodies of two unidentified youths in Sonarpur, on the southern fringes of the city, on Monday. The youths were in their 20s. Police suspect they were murdered elsewhere.

 Nitu Singh, a 29-year-old housewife, committed suicide by hanging herself from the ceiling of her Manmohan Mukherjee Lane residence, under Shibpur police station, on Sunday. Nitu?s husband Barun Singh was not at home. The body was spotted by one of his friends, who came to meet him. Police were informed around 5 pm. The woman has left a note citing conjugal problems as the reason for killing herself, police said. Nitu and Barun married two years ago and had no children. No complaint has been lodged. 

 Vizag Steel, represented by J. Rahul and A.G.K. Murthy, has won the Calcutta finals of Tata Crucible ? The Business Quiz 2005. The team beat five other finalists ? ITC Limited, ABP Group, Kothari Marketing, ICICI Bank and Gameplan ? and will take part in the national finals to be held in Mumbai on July 24. The quizmaster at the Calcutta event was Giri Balasubramaniam (Pickbrain).

 INS Beas, a state-of-the-art guided missile frigate, was commissioned by navy chief Arun Prakash on Monday. The frigate was built by Garden Reach Shipbuilders and Engineers and is equipped with sophisticated and indigenous weapons and sensor suit.

 The BOC Oxyline? service, which provides oxygen during emergency at any time of the day, has opened a helpline ? 9831277777. The agency has a range of products, including medical oxygen with accessories, nitrous oxide and oxygen concentrators.

 Ten people have been arrested in connection with the violence on Premchand Boral Street, under Muchipara police station, on Sunday night.

 With reference to the story ?Felony fight shuts down fitness centre?, published in Metro on July 11, it is clarified that Super City Fitness Centre, on Rajdanga Main Road, Kasba, has not shut its doors due to the legal battle. While the services have been curtailed, the gym is open and functioning normally.

